node.text:
Day Eight of the @Paralympics saw the changing of the guard, as old heroes made way for new idols.⁠
⁠
On the same day the most successful para swimmer ever, Daniel Dias, took to the pool for the final time, Saeid Afrooz won his first Paralympic medal with a world record throw in the javelin. Meanwhile, badminton made its debut, with more history beckoning when its maiden champions are crowned later this week.⁠
⁠
You can keep up to date with that action, as well as everything else going on in Tokyo, via the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
#Tokyo2020 #Paralympics

node.text:
At 24-years-old Belinda Bencic became the first female Swiss player to win an Olympic singles title, which she followed up with a silver medal in the doubles to cap the greatest fortnight of her career. 🥇🥈⁠
⁠
Those successes tasted even sweeter for Bencic after enduring numerous injury setbacks in recent years, which also caused her to miss the Rio 2016 Games. ⁠
⁠
Her perseverance led her to not just be an Olympian, but an Olympic gold medalist. 👏 ⁠
⁠

node.text:
Day Seven at the #Tokyo2020 @Paralympics is complete, and records continue to fall.

Robiel Yankiel Sol Cervantes won the men’s long jump T47 in style by breaking the Paralympic record with his first attempt, while on the track, Marcel Hug smashed the 1500m T54 world record.

Meanwhile, Reece Dunn grabbed another gold and his second WR of the Games in the 200m individual medley SM14, as limits keep being redefined in Tokyo.

What’s been your most inspiring moment so far? Let us know in the comments.

#Tokyo2020 #Paralympics
